## pix2pix论文笔记

### 1. Abstract

Investigating CGANs as a general-purpose solution to image-to-image translation

### 2. Introduction

We define automatic image-to-image translation as the task of translating one possible representation of a scene into another, given sufficient training data

**NOTE**: for loss function

> Euclidean distance, it will tend to produce blurry results. This is because Euclidean distance is minimized by averaging all plausible outputs, which causes blurring.
>
> Other Solution: 
>
> *Energy-based generative adversarial network* 

### 3. Related Work

##### Structured losses for image modeling

Image-to-image translation problems are often formulated as **per-pixel** task, and it treats the output as “unstructured” which means pixels are considered independent. 

The CGAN learn a structured loss in which the loss can penalize any possible structure that differs from output and target.

##### Conditional GANs 

Several other papers have also used GANs for image-to-image mappings, but only applied the GAN unconditionally, relying on other terms (such as L2 regression) to force the output to be conditioned on the input.

### 4. Method

##### Objective

Previous approaches have found it beneficial to mix the GAN objective with a more traditional loss, such as L2 . The $G$ looks near to the ground truth in this. We
using L1 as L1 encourages less blurring:
$$
Loss_{L_1} = E_{x,y,z}[|| y-G(x,z) ||_1]
$$
The final objective is
$$
G = \arg \min_G \max_D L_{cGAN}(G,D)+\lambda L_{L_1}(G)
$$

##### Generator with skips

Many previous solutions used AE. For image translation, there is a great deal of low-level information shared between the input and output, and it would be desirable to shuttle this information directly across the net.

To give $G$ a means to circumvent the bottleneck for information like this, we add skip connections as “U-Net”.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) 

##### Markovian discriminator (PatchGAN)

L2 loss – and L1– produces blurry results.Cause’ it capture the low frequcy structure.

This motivates restricting the GAN discriminator to only model high-frequency structure

So, it is sufficient to restrict our attention to local image patches. 

Therefore, we design PatchGAN – that only penalizes structure at the scale of patches.

By classifying if each $N ×N$ patch is real or fake, averaging all responses to provide the ultimate output of D.

##### Optimization and inference

This approach to batch normalization, when the batch size is set to 1, has been termed “instance normalization” and has been demonstrated to be effective at image generation tasks

### 5. Experiments

#####  Analysis of the objective function

L1 alone leads to reasonable but blurry results. The cGAN alone gives much sharper results but introduces visual artifacts on certain applications. Adding both terms together reduces these artifacts.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) 

##### Analysis of the generator architecture

A U-Net architecture allows low-level information to shortcut across the network, and lead to better results.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) 

##### From PixelGANs to PatchGANs to ImageGANs

We test the effect of varying the patch size N of our discriminator receptive fields, from a 1 × 1 “PixelGAN” to a full 286 × 286 “ImageGAN”.
